e":"1330–Deceased","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1360":"1360","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","Abt 1382":"about 1382","1379":"1379","1443":"1443","1366":"1366","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1463":"1463","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Arncliffe, Yorkshire, England":"Arncliffe, Yorkshire, England","Beeston, Leeds, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Beeston, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Leeds Minster, Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds Minster, Leeds, Yorkshire, England","Woddsome, West Riding, York, England":"York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Leeds, Humber, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Leeds, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mauleverer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>mal leverier</i> ‘bad harrier’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Mauleverer was born in 1360, his father, William Mauleverer, was 30 and his mother, Catharine Boswell, was 30. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Lady Elizabeth Barlow. He died in 1443, at the age of 83, and was buried in Leeds Minster, Leeds, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1360–1443":"1360–1443","1355–1398":"1355–1398","1366–1387":"1366–1387","1373–Female":"1373–Surnud","1379–1463":"1379–1463","1382–Male":"1382–Surnud","1387–Female":"1387–Surnud","1393–Female":"1393–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1360":"1360","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","Abt 1382":"umbes 1382","1379":"1379","1443":"1443","1366":"1366","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1463":"1463","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Arncliffe, Yorkshire, England":"Arncliffe, Yorkshire, England","Beeston, Leeds, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Beeston, West Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leeds Minster, Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds Minster, Leeds, Yorkshire, England","Woddsome, West Riding, York, England":"York, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leeds, Humber, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Leeds, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1360–1443":"1360–1443","1355–1398":"1355–1398","1366–1387":"1366–1387","1373–Female":"1373–Kuollut","1379–1463":"1379–1463","1382–Male":"1382–Kuollut","1387–Female":"1387–Kuollut","1393–Female":"1393–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1